Personal Loan Campaign Modelling¶

by Michele Casalgrandi

Background¶

AllLife is a US bank. The majority of AllLife customers are depositors (liability customers).

The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is low. The bank is interested in converting its liability customers to personal loan customers and raise earnings through interest on loans.

While the past year campaign had a good conversion rate of 9%, the marketing department is working on better targeted campaigns in order to improve the success rate

Objectives¶

  1. Predict whether a liability customer will buy a personal loan
  2. Identify which variables are most significant
  3. Identify which segment of customers should be targeted more

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customers age in completed years
  • Experience: number of years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank?
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities?
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)?

Data Summary¶

  • ID. Each row has a unique 'ID'. As we are not interested in individual customers as such but in the aggregate, we will drop the ID.

  • Age. Ranges from 23 to 67. Average is ~45 and so is the median, suggesting there is little, if any skew.

  • Experience. There appear to be one or more invalid entries (e.g. minimum is -3). We will need to address that.

  • Income. Range seems reasonable. There is high std deviation and appears to be skewed with outliers.

  • ZipCode. It is represented numerically but it's a categorical variable with 467 levels. We'll probably encode the top 10 or so and group the remaining in 'Other'

  • Family. Categorical with four levels. Mean of 2.4 and median of 2.

  • CCAvg. Ranges from 0 to 10 with some skew.

  • Education. Categorical with three levels.

  • Mortgage. Most observation have 0 (no mortgage). Mean is 56 and std deviation is high at 102

  • Personal_Loan, Securities_Account, CD_Account, Online and CreditCard are categorical variables represented numerically with two levels (0,1)

# Define function to convert zipcode to 'Other' as appropriate
def bin_zipcode(zipcode):
    ''' Returns "Other" for zipcodes not in zipcode_top_n
    Returns a string'''
    if zipcode in zipcode_top_n:
        return str(zipcode)
    else:
        return 'Other'

# define function to plot histogram and boxplot for a feature
def histogram_boxplot(feature, figsize=(15, 10), bins=None):
    """Boxplot and histogram combined
    feature: 1-d feature array
    figsize: size of fig (default (15,10))
    bins: number of bins (default None / auto)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.distplot(
        feature, kde=True, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.distplot(
        feature, kde=False, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        feature.mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        feature.median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# Function to create barplots that indicate percentage for each category.

def perc_on_bar(z):
    '''
    plot
    feature: categorical feature
    the function won't work if a column is passed in hue parameter
    '''

    total = len(z) # length of the column
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    #plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    ax = sns.countplot(z,palette='Paired')
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # hieght of the plot
        
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size = 12) # annotate the percentage 
    plt.show() # show the plot

### Function to plot stacked bar charts for categorical columns
def stacked_plot(data, x, y):
    ''' Plot stacked bar charts.
        data = dataframe,
        x = categorical column to plot across x axis
        y = categorical column to stack
    '''
    sns.set()
    ## crosstab 
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[x],data[y],margins=True)
    print(tab1)
    print('-'*120)
    ## visualising the cross tab
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[x],data[y],normalize='index')
    tab.plot(kind='bar',stacked=True,figsize=(17,7))
    plt.legend(loc='lower left', frameon=False,)
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1,1))
    plt.show()

Summary of EDA and pre-processing¶

Data Description

  • There are no missing values in dataset
  • All original variables were stored as numeric types
  • Dependent variable is Personal_Loan which is of categorical type (0=No, 1=Yes)

Data Cleaning

  • Experience had negative values that were converted to positive.

Observations from EDA

  • ID. Customer id with unique values for each observation
  • Age. Ranges from 23 to 67. Average is ~45 and so is the median.
    Roughly uniform between 30 and 63 and then it tapers on both ends. No outliers.
  • Experience. Roughly uniform between 1 and 36 and tapers at the ends. Slightly skewed to the right.
  • Income. Mean of 74, median of 64. There is high std deviation and is skewed to the right with many outliers.
  • ZipCode. Represented numerically but it's a categorical variable with 467 levels.
    The top 3 ZIP codes account for approximately 400 customers (out of 5000).
  • Family. Categorical with four levels. Majority is Family of size 1 (29%) followed by 3, 2 and 4.
  • CCAvg. Mean of 1.94 and median of 1.75. Ranges from 0 to 10.
    Most values are under 3, skewed to the right with long tail.
    Log transformed into CCAvg_log.
  • Education. Categorical with three levels.
    42% have undergraduate education (1), followed by Advanced/Professional (3) at 30% and last Graduate (2) at 28%
  • Mortgage. Most observation have 0 (no mortgage). Mean is 56 and std deviation is high at 102.
    Mortgage was binned into 5 levels (Mortgage_bin).
  • Personal_Loan. Categorical with two levels. 90.4% of customers do not have a personal loan with the bank.
  • Securities_Account. Categorical with two levels. 10% of customers have a securities account.
  • CD_Account. Categorical with two levels. 94% of customers do not have a certificate of deposit account.
  • Online. Categorical with two levels. 60% of customers use online banking.

  • CreditCard. Categorical with two levels. 71% of customers use a credit card issued by another bank

  • Personal_Loan vs. Age. Customers with a personal loan are evenly distributed across Age

  • Personal_Loan vs. Experience. Customers with a personal loan are evenly distributed across Experience
  • Personal_Loan vs. Income. Customers who have a personal loan tend to have higher Income
  • Personal_Loan vs. CCAvg_log. Customers who have a personal loan tend to have higher CCAvg_log
  • Personal_Loan vs. Education. A smaller percentage of customers with Undergraduate education (1) accepted loans.
    Graduate (2) and Advanced (3) had similar higher rates.
  • Personal_Loan vs. Mortgage_bin. As the mortgage amount grows, customers accepted personal loans at a higher rate.
  • Personal_Loan vs. Securities_Account. Customers with a Securities account tended to accept personal loan at a slightly higher rate.
  • Personal_Loan vs. CD_Account. Customers with a CD Account accepted personal loans at a significantly higher rate than those without one.
  • Personal_Loan vs. Online. The use of online banking did not correspond to a significant difference in the acceptance rate of personal loans
  • Personal_Loan vs. CreditCard. The use of another banks's credit card did not correspond to a significant difference in the acceptance rate of personal loans.

Data Pre-processing

  • Family, Education, Securities_Account, CD_Account, Online, CreditCard were cast to category dtype without any additional processing
  • ZIPCode was binned into the top 10 ZIP codes (highest count) plus 'Other' which includes all remaining ZIP codes.
    ZIPCode_cat levels: 94720, 94305, 95616, 90095, 93106, 93943, 92037, 91320, 94025, 91711, Other
  • Mortgage was binned into 5 levels to manage the skew and the many zero values (no mortgage).
    Mortgage_bin levels: 0, 1-100, 101-200, 201-300, 301-400, > 400
  • To correct for skew and distribution CCAvg was log transformed into CCAvg_log
  • ID was dropped as we are not interested in the identity of each customer
  • Experience was dropped as it is almost perfectly correlated (0.99) with Age

Model building¶

Model Evaluation¶

  • Positive: customer accepted a personal loan (1)
  • Negative: customer did not accept a personal loan (0)

Predictions¶

  • False Positive (FP): Predicting the customer will accept loan offer but actually it will not get accepted.
    • We might spend time and resources on customers that are not receptive to the offer, leading to ineffective campaign.
  • False Negative (FN): Predicting the customer will not accept a loan but actually it would have been accepted.
    • We would fail to target customers who could be converted to personal loan customers. This will lead to lost opportunities and lower revenues than what might have been otherwise.

We consider the cost of False Negatives higher than False Positive.

Accuracy and ROC-AUC are not good performance metrics as the predicted class is imbalanced.

We could use Recall as a metric to be optimized. However, we cannot just maximize it; a model that always predicts Positive will achieve $Recall = 1$ and provide no value to the business.

Based on the above consideratons, we'll optimize Precision and Recall.

Logistic Regression¶

We will first use a logistic regression model.

def get_metrics_score(model,train,test,train_y,test_y,threshold=0.5,print_values=True,roc=False):
    '''
    Function to calculate different metric scores of the model - Accuracy, Recall, Precision, and F1 score
    model: classifier to predict values of X
    train, test: Independent features
    train_y,test_y: Dependent variable
    threshold: thresold for classifiying the observation as 1
    flag: If the flag is set to True then only the print statements showing different will be displayed. 
        The default value is set to True.
    roc: If the roc is set to True then only roc score will be displayed. The default value is set to False.
    '''
    # defining an empty list to store train and test results
    
    score_list=[] 
    
    pred_train = (model.predict_proba(train)[:,1]>threshold)
    pred_test = (model.predict_proba(test)[:,1]>threshold)

    pred_train = np.round(pred_train)
    pred_test = np.round(pred_test)
    
    train_acc = metrics.accuracy_score(pred_train,train_y)
    test_acc = metrics.accuracy_score(pred_test,test_y)
    
    train_recall = metrics.recall_score(train_y,pred_train)
    test_recall = metrics.recall_score(test_y,pred_test)
    
    train_precision = metrics.precision_score(train_y,pred_train)
    test_precision = metrics.precision_score(test_y,pred_test)
    
    train_f1 = metrics.f1_score(train_y,pred_train)
    test_f1 = metrics.f1_score(test_y,pred_test)
    
    
    score_list.extend((train_acc,test_acc,train_recall,test_recall,train_precision,test_precision,train_f1,test_f1))
        
    
    if print_values == True: 
        print("Accuracy - training      : ", train_acc)
        print("Accuracy - test          : ", test_acc)
        print("Recall - training        : ", train_recall)
        print("Recall - test            : ", test_recall)
        print("Precision - training     : ", train_precision)
        print("Precision - test         : ", test_precision)
        print("F1 - training            : ", train_f1)
        print("F1 - test                : ", test_f1)
   
    if roc == True:
        pred_train_prob = model.predict_proba(train)[:,1]
        pred_test_prob = model.predict_proba(test)[:,1]
        print("ROC-AUC Score - training : ", metrics.roc_auc_score(train_y,pred_train))
        print("ROC-AUC Score - test     : ", metrics.roc_auc_score(test_y,pred_test))
    
    return score_list # returning the list with train and test scores
In [615]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(model, X, y_actual, threshold=0.5):
    '''Plot confusion matrix from model, X and y_actual.
    '''
#    y_predict = model.predict(X)
    y_predict = (model.predict_proba(X)[:,1]>threshold)
    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_actual, y_predict)
    # print(cm.flatten())
    # https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.metrics.confusion_matrix.html
    TN = cm[0,0]
    FP = cm[0,1]
    FN = cm[1,0]
    TP = cm[1,1]
    # print(f'TN:{TN}, FN:{FN}, TP:{TP}, FP:{FP}')
    accuracy  = (TP + TN) / (TN+FN+TP+FP) 
    precision = TP / (TP + FP)
    recall    = TP / (TP + FN)
    f1_score  = 2 * precision * recall / (precision + recall)
    scores = "\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}\nPrecision={:0.3f}\nRecall={:0.3f}\nF1 Score={:0.3f}".format(accuracy,precision,recall,f1_score)
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["0","1"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ["Predict 0","Predict 1"]])
    group_names = ['TN', 'FP','FN','TP']
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                     cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}\n{v3}" for v1, v2, v3 in
          zip(group_names,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels, fmt='', cmap='Spectral')
    print(scores)

def plot_prec_recall_vs_tresh(precisions, recalls, thresholds):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,7))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
    ax.plot(thresholds, precisions[:-1], 'b--', label='precision')
    ax.plot(thresholds, recalls[:-1], 'g--', label = 'recall')
    plt.xlabel('Threshold')
    plt.legend(loc='lower left')
    plt.ylim([0,1])
    ax.set_xticks(np.arange(0,1.05,0.05))
    ax.grid(markevery=10, which='major')
plot_prec_recall_vs_tresh(prec, rec, tre)
plt.show()

Logistic regression coefficients interpretation¶

  • Age: Increasing the age by 1 unit will increase the odds of a customer accepting a loan by 1.0025 times. An increase of 0.25%
  • Income: Increasing income by 1 will increase the odds of a customer accepting a loan by 1.058 times or 5.8%.
  • Family: A family of 3 increase the odds of accepting a loan by 1.22 times compared to a descrease in odds for other family size.
  • Education: A customer with Education of 2 (Graduate) or 3 (Advanced) have higher odds than one with Education 1 (Undergraduate) to accept a loan offer
  • _SecuritiesAccount, Online and CreditCard: Customer with Securities account, who do online banking and who have credit card with another bank have lower odds of accepting a Personal Loan by 0.26, 0.54 and 0.44 times respectively.
  • _CDAccount: Customers with a CD Account have higher odds of accepting a loan by 35 times.
  • ZIPCode: ZIPCode has varying factors ranging from 1.32 times higher odds for 94305 to 0.47 times lower odds.
  • Mortgage: Mortage '301 - 400' shows an increase odds by 1.10 times, as compared to the other mortgage bins that show a decrease in odds.
  • _CCAvg_log': an in increase of 1 unit in CCAvg_log raises the odds of accepting a loan by 2.2 times

Decision Tree - Reducing Overfitting and Complexity¶

Prepruning - Grid Search¶

In [634]:
# import required libraries
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
In [635]:
# Define grid parameters
parameters = {
    "max_depth": range(1, 11),
    "criterion": ['gini','entropy'],
    "splitter": ['best', 'random'],
    "min_impurity_decrease": [0.00001, 0.0001, 0.001, 0.01],
    "max_features": ['log2','sqrt']
}

# Even though we want to optimixe Recall, maximizing Recall alone will create a model with
# very high number of False Positive
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score)

# Run the grid search
grid = GridSearchCV(dtm, parameters, scoring=scorer, cv=5)
grid = grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Get the best estimator
prep_best_estimator = grid.best_estimator_

# Fit the best estimator
prep_best_estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

                       random_state=1)

Train decision trees using the alphas.

In [643]:
clfs = []
for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas:
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(
        random_state=1, ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha, class_weight='balanced'
    )
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    clfs.append(clf)
print(
    "Number of nodes in the last tree is: {} with ccp_alpha: {}".format(
        clfs[-1].tree_.node_count, ccp_alphas[-1]
    )
)

Number of nodes in the last tree is: 1 with ccp_alpha: 0.29537927599923186

We will remove the last alpha since it builds a trivial tree with one node and has no predictive value to the business.

In [644]:
# remove last model
clfs = clfs[:-1]
# remove last alpha
ccp_alphas = ccp_alphas[:-1]

# plot node count vs alpha
node_counts = [clf.tree_.node_count for clf in clfs]
depth = [clf.tree_.max_depth for clf in clfs]
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(10, 7))
ax[0].plot(ccp_alphas, node_counts, marker="o", drawstyle="steps-post")
ax[0].set_xlabel("alpha")
ax[0].set_ylabel("number of nodes")
ax[0].set_title("Number of nodes vs alpha")
ax[1].plot(ccp_alphas, depth, marker="o", drawstyle="steps-post")
ax[1].set_xlabel("alpha")
ax[1].set_ylabel("depth of tree")
ax[1].set_title("Depth vs alpha")
fig.tight_layout()
Plot f1 scores for train and test against the various alphas¶
In [645]:
# Get f1 scores from TRAIN data set
f1_train = []
for clf in clfs:
    pred_train = clf.predict(X_train)
    values_train = metrics.f1_score(y_train, pred_train)
    f1_train.append(values_train)
    
# Get f1 scores from TEST data set
f1_test = []
for clf in clfs:
    pred_test = clf.predict(X_test)
    values_test = metrics.f1_score(y_test, pred_test)
    f1_test.append(values_test)
In [646]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 5))
ax.set_xlabel("alpha")
ax.set_ylabel("F1-score")
ax.set_title("F1-score vs alpha for training and testing sets")
ax.plot(
    ccp_alphas, f1_train, marker="o", label="train", drawstyle="steps-post",
)
ax.set_xticks(np.arange(0,0.05,0.002))
ax.grid(markevery=10, which='major')
ax.plot(ccp_alphas, f1_test, marker="o", label="test", drawstyle="steps-post")
ax.legend()
plt.show()

The most important feature is Income, followed by Education_1 (Undergraduate), CCAvg_log (log of credit card avg expenditures), Family 3 and 4 and last CD_Account.

Decision Tree Features Importance Interpretation¶

  • Customers with Income <= 92.5 are more likely to accept a loan if they also have a CD account
  • Customers with Income above > 92.5 are more likely to accept a loan:
    • if their education is higher than Undergraduate, or,
    • if their education is undergraduate, and family size is 3 or 4
  • Customers are more likely to accept a loan if their monthly credit card average spending is higher than approx. 3000 USD.

Conclusions¶

  • We have analyzed data for bank customers and used Logistic Regression and Decision Tree models to create a predictive model.
  • The models can be used to predict whether a customer is going to accept a loan offer from the bank
  • Although we considered the lost opportunity cost of a False Negative higher than a False Positive we optimized Recall and f1-score rather than Recall alone. A model that has high Recall but also very high rate of False Positives (low Precision) is not informative.
  • The Decision tree (DT) model chosen shows higher performance metrics than the logistic regression (LR). The best DT model has an f1-score of 0.85 with a Recall of 0.94 vs f1-score of 0.73 and Recall of 0.738 for the LR.
  • The decision tree fit to the data indicates that the most important predictors are Income, Education, Credit Card expenditure and Family size.

Recommendations¶

  • Use the predictive model to identify current customers who are very likely to accept a loan offer and target them as part of a campaign.
  • Based on the decision tree model, ZIP code is not a significant predictor of accepting a loan offer. Campaign should not focus on ZIP code as determinant of campaign strategy.
  • Customers with high credit cards transactions values are more likely to accept a loan. A campaign should target those customers.
  • Low acceptance rates of loan offers by smaller families of one or two might indicate there is an opportunitiy to target more specifically those segments to increase the acceptance rate.
  • Lower acceptance rates of customers with Undergraduate education, suggests there might be an opportunity to raise acceptance rates in this customer segment.
  • The models indicate that income is the best predictor for accepting a loan offer. Future campaigns should target high income customers with tailored loan offers.
